\begin{document}
$$o\left({{F_H},{F_E}} \right) = W\left({\lambda \cdot Attn\left({{F_H},{F_E}} \right) + V{F_E}} \right),$$
\end{document}

The age distribution of the training samples is inhomogeneous, which presents a significant challenge for the regression problem. Given that age is a continuous variable, we proposed the DecadeCE Loss, which transforms the regression problem into an ordered multiclassification problem, with each class spanning 10 years. The DecadeCE Loss samples numerical labels from a Gaussian distribution for each range to obtain class vectors, preventing precision lost. The soft cross-entropy between these vectors and the model output is then calculated. For a given age y, it is first discretized into a distribution that follows the N(y, σ), calculated as:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$p\left(t \right) ={\mathrm{1\over{\sqrt{2\pi}{\sigma^2}}}\exp\left({-{{{{\left({t-y}\right)}^2}}\over{2{\sigma^2}}}}\right)}$$
\end{document}

where t=5,15,…,95, representing the midpoints of each decade. The numerical y value is converted to vector Y containing 10 levels of probability as
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$${Y^{\left(t \right)}} = p(t)/ma{x_t}(p(t)).$$
\end{document}

Then, the loss between a target Y and a predicted ŷ is computed by weighted cross-entropy, expressed as:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$Loss = - {1 \over {10}}\sum\nolimits_t {\left[{{Y^{\left(t \right)}}log\left({{{\hat Y}^{\left(t \right)}}} \right) + \left({1 - {Y^{\left(t \right)}}} \right){\mathrm{log}}\left({1 - {{\hat Y}^{\left(t \right)}}} \right)} \right]}$$
\end{document}

During model inference, the 10 class outputs of the neural network are passed through the softmax function to obtain their corresponding predictive probabilities, calculated as:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$\hat P = softmax\left({\hat Y} \right)$$
\end{document}

Therefore, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$P= \{ {\hat P^{\left(t \right)}}|t = 5,15, \ldots ,95\}$\end{document} is composed of probabilities from 10 classes. We define the ordered median predictive probability as the output BA value of the model to enhance the stability of converting continuous classification results into regression values. It is calculated as follows:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$P\left(x \right) = {1 \over {10}}\sum\nolimits_{i = 1}^x {\sum\nolimits_t {{{\hat P}^{\left(t \right)}} \cdot {1_{[t - 5{\mathrm{\lt}}i \le t + 5]}}} }$$
\end{document}
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$BA = {\mathrm{min}}\left({x\mid P\left(x \right) \ge 0.5} \right)$$
\end{document}

The MAE and Pearson correlation (R) are used to evaluate the predictive performance of the model across varied age ranges.9 They are denoted as:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$MAE = {1 \over N}\mathop \sum \limits_{i = 1}^N \left| {{{\hat y}_i} - {y_i}} \right|$$
\end{document}
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$R = {{{{\mathop \sum \nolimits}^}\left({y - \bar y} \right)\left({\hat y- \overline {\hat y} } \right)} \over {\sqrt {{{\mathop \sum \nolimits}^}{{\left({y - \bar y} \right)}^2}{{\mathop \sum \nolimits}^}{{\left({\hat y- \overline {\hat y} } \right)}^2}} }},$$
\end{document}

Next, to assess the effectiveness of proposed DecadeCE Loss in model training, we compared it to two commonly used regression losses: MSE Loss and Huber Loss. They are calculated as follows:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$MSE\,{\mathrm{ }}Loss\left({y,\hat y} \right) = {\mathrm{ }}{\left({{y_i} - {{\hat y}_i}} \right)^2}$$
\end{document}
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$$Huber\,Loss\left({{y_i},{{\hat y}_i}} \right) = \left \{ \matrix{ 0.5{\left({{y_i} - {{\hat y}_i}} \right)^2},\,\,\,if\left| {{y_i} - {{\hat y}_i}} \right| \le 5 \hfill \cr 5\left({\left| {{y_i} - {{\hat y}_i}} \right| - 2.5} \right),\,\,\,if\left| {{y_i} - {{\hat y}_i}} \right| \le 5 \hfill \cr} \right.$$
\end{document}
